Thermal spray method has been used to prepare composite materials of support and photocatalysts in a large scale. As a highly porous and chemically inert media, perlite granules can act as a good adsorbent and support for TiO2 photocatalysts. M. Giannouri et al. presents the one-step synthesis of the TiO2/perlite composites by flame spray pyrolysis (FSP) processing. The composite samples exhibited improved photocatalytic activity in comparison with commercial TiO2 P25. However, the disinfection performance of TiO2/perlite composites is yet to be reported (Ref 102) TiO2-hydroxyapatite (HAp) hybrid films were proved to be candidates for photocatalytic decomposition of germs, viruses by Nakajima et al. through spray pyrolysis deposition (SPD) method (Ref 103). Liu et al. prepared photocatalytic TiO2-HA coatings with significantly promoted adherence of E. coli bacteria (Ref 104), since HA is essentially biomedical material that bacteria like to stay on. It was also revealed that the coatings consisting of 10Â wt.% HA showed the best photocatalytic activity, which is comparable to that exhibited by immobilized Degussa P25 coating. However, the photocatalytic disinfection mechanisms of E. coli were not discussed in the study. To further investigate the antibacterial mechanism, Huang et al. fabricated two types of TiO2-HA nanocomposites (TiO2-HA, TiO2-HA-rGO) by liquid flame spray deposition (Ref 100, 105). HA-enwrapped TiO2 nanocomposite powder was fabricated by using P25 particles as nucleation sites. HA in the composite powder acts as bait attracting approaching of bacteria and pushing them to TiO2. Moreover, the vacancies formed on the surface of excited phosphate group (PO43-\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
